00:30:57,805 --> 00:31:00,000
I use it to change the channels.

248
00:31:10,752 --> 00:31:12,083
I'm sorry.

249
00:31:14,522 --> 00:31:17,616
You wouldn't think of driving
without your rear-view mirror...

250
00:31:17,692 --> 00:31:20,820
...and yet some people still drive
without a fuzz buster.

251
00:31:49,424 --> 00:31:52,985
When they unwrapped the chopsticks
to be used by the Chinese guests...

252
00:31:53,061 --> 00:31:56,292
...the packages were clearly stamped
'Made in Taiwan. '

253
00:31:57,365 --> 00:32:01,426
I know it's important to stay informed
of all the latest events, but...

254
00:32:01,803 --> 00:32:05,569
...I find there's so much to assimilate
it can become quite muddling at times.

255
00:32:05,640 --> 00:32:09,633
Until they placed the chopsticks around
the table. If the Chinese were upset...

256
00:32:11,846 --> 00:32:15,043
'I even put that basketball
underneath my pillow

257
00:32:15,683 --> 00:32:18,413
'Maybe that's why I can't sleep at night

258
00:32:19,120 --> 00:32:21,054
'I need help, ladies and gentlemen

259
00:32:21,723 --> 00:32:24,191
'I need someone to stand beside me

260
00:32:24,425 --> 00:32:29,328
'I need someone to set a pit for me
at the free-throw diamond line

261
00:32:30,331 --> 00:32:32,196
'Someone I can pass to

262
00:32:32,600 --> 00:32:35,569
'Someone to hit the open line
on the given goal

263
00:32:35,970 --> 00:32:37,904
'Some cheerleaders to help me out

264
00:32:49,851 --> 00:32:52,877
'I want everybody in the whole stadium
to stand up and sing'

265
00:33:50,578 --> 00:33:51,567
Ma'am.

266
00:33:52,113 --> 00:33:55,241
Wilson, will you take Mr. Gardiner
to the third-floor guest suite?

267
00:33:55,316 --> 00:33:56,283
Yes, ma'am.

268
00:33:56,384 --> 00:33:59,182
I'll see you after Dr. Allenby
has a look at your leg.

269
00:33:59,487 --> 00:34:01,352
Thank you. Yes... Yes.

270
00:34:23,478 --> 00:34:25,878
I've never been in one of these before.

271
00:34:27,749 --> 00:34:30,912
It's one of Mr. Rand's. Since he's been ill.

272
00:34:32,854 --> 00:34:33,843
I see.

273
00:34:36,557 --> 00:34:38,991
Does it have a television?

274
00:34:40,495 --> 00:34:44,591
No. But Mr. Rand does have one
with an electric motor.

275
00:34:45,299 --> 00:34:47,767
That way he can get around by himself.

276
00:34:51,973 --> 00:34:54,100
How long do we stay in here?

277
00:34:54,742 --> 00:34:55,800
How long?

278
00:34:56,711 --> 00:34:59,737
I don't know.
We'll see what the doctor says.

279
00:35:15,963 --> 00:35:19,797
I've seen it done before,
in a film on television.

280
00:35:19,867 --> 00:35:21,300
This won't hurt at all.

281
00:35:24,272 --> 00:35:25,432
It did hurt.

282
00:35:26,040 --> 00:35:27,800
Now, there's no apparent damage to the bone.

283
00:35:28,000 --> 00:35:30,477
But just to be sure,
I have Wilson wheel you down for an x-ray.

284
00:35:30,978 --> 00:35:31,945
X-ray?

285
00:35:33,181 --> 00:35:36,981
By the way, Mr. Gardiner,
I'd like to ask you something straight out.

286
00:35:37,151 --> 00:35:38,846
- Straight out?
- Yes, sir.

287
00:35:40,254 --> 00:35:43,815
Are you planning on making
any sort of claim against the Rand's?

288
00:35:46,460 --> 00:35:47,449
Claim.

289
00:35:50,331 --> 00:35:52,094
That's what Thomas asked me.

290
00:35:52,166 --> 00:35:54,964
Thomas? Oh, you can pull
your trousers up now if you like.

291
00:35:57,305 --> 00:35:59,068
Who... Who's Thomas?

292
00:36:00,041 --> 00:36:02,236
Thomas Franklin. He's an attorney.

293
00:36:02,577 --> 00:36:04,101
- An attorney?
- Yes.

294
00:36:04,679 --> 00:36:07,671
Then you wish to handle this matter
through your attorneys?

295
00:36:09,350 --> 00:36:11,580
There's no need for a claim.

296
00:36:13,621 --> 00:36:15,646
I don't even know what they look like.

297
00:36:21,963 --> 00:36:23,123
Well, then.

298
00:36:24,198 --> 00:36:26,758
You caught me off guard there,
I must admit.

299
00:36:28,202 --> 00:36:29,328
Thank you.

300
00:36:30,872 --> 00:36:34,399
Now, the only thing we have
to look out for is minor hemorrhaging...

301
00:36:34,475 --> 00:36:37,444
...which isn't serious,
but could cause trouble later on.

302
00:36:37,545 --> 00:36:39,536
Tell me, Mr. Gardiner...

303
00:36:39,947 --> 00:36:43,178
...would it be possible for you
to stay here for a day or two...

304
00:36:43,251 --> 00:36:44,718
...so we could keep an eye on it?

305
00:36:44,785 --> 00:36:46,753
Oh, yes, I could stay here.

306
00:36:47,955 --> 00:36:50,685
- Does this house have a garden?
- Oh, why, yes. Many.

307
00:36:52,159 --> 00:36:53,091
Good.

308
00:36:53,160 --> 00:36:55,685
- Keep your weight off that leg, Mr. Gardiner.
- Yes.

309
00:36:56,497 --> 00:37:00,558
Mr. Wilson, please wheel Mr. Gardiner in
for x-rays after you've finished unpacking.

310
00:37:00,635 --> 00:37:02,193
- Yes, Doctor.
- Thank you.

311
00:37:06,607 --> 00:37:10,008
Ever watch a game on TV and see
the players chugging down this stuff?

312
00:37:10,111 --> 00:37:11,237
Ever wonder why?

313
00:37:23,057 --> 00:37:25,548
Oh, I miss you so when I'm out.
How're you feeling?

314
00:37:26,661 --> 00:37:27,889
No headaches?

315
00:37:28,296 --> 00:37:30,264
No, it's been a fairly good day.

316
00:37:32,033 --> 00:37:35,332
- Better than yours, so I've been told.
- Oh, you heard about it?

317
00:37:36,370 --> 00:37:37,962
I may be a shut-in, but...

318
00:37:38,572 --> 00:37:40,699
I'm sorry you had to go through all that.

319
00:37:40,775 --> 00:37:44,040
It was nothing, nothing, really.
It just sounded worse than it was.

320
00:37:44,478 --> 00:37:47,413
And Mr. Gardiner is a very reasonable man.

321
00:37:48,749 --> 00:37:49,875
Reasonable.

322
00:37:50,618 --> 00:37:53,519
I'd like to meet a reasonable man
for a change.

323
00:37:54,655 --> 00:37:56,850
Why don't you ask this Robinson
for dinner?

324
00:37:56,924 --> 00:38:00,360
Gardiner. Gardiner. Chauncey.
Chauncey Gardiner.

325
00:38:01,162 --> 00:38:02,424
Gardiner.

326
00:38:03,597 --> 00:38:05,827
You think you're well enough
for dinner, Ben?

327
00:38:08,002 --> 00:38:11,904
Constance, I want fresh blood for dinner.

328
00:38:12,540 --> 00:38:13,564
Yes, sir.

329
00:38:19,647 --> 00:38:21,774
I'll have them set another place.

330
00:38:38,666 --> 00:38:41,100
My God, Eve, you'll freeze.

331
00:38:41,469 --> 00:38:43,369
No. I just...

332
00:38:44,805 --> 00:38:47,239
I just wanted to get some fresh air.

333
00:38:48,843 --> 00:38:50,333
How's Mr. Gardiner?

334
00:38:52,113 --> 00:38:54,138
Doesn't seem to be too serious.

335
00:38:54,281 --> 00:38:57,614
But it's a rather large contusion
and I'd like to keep an eye on him.

336
00:38:57,852 --> 00:39:00,753
So I suggested that he stay here
for a couple of days.

337
00:39:00,821 --> 00:39:01,810
Here?

338
00:39:02,957 --> 00:39:05,721
Mr. Gardiner stay here? Why?
Is that necessary?

339
00:39:07,228 --> 00:39:10,789
No, not necessary, but helpful.

340
00:39:12,466 --> 00:39:15,526
Don't worry,
he might be a breath of fresh air.

341
00:39:18,806 --> 00:39:20,535
He is different, isn't he?

342
00:39:21,809 --> 00:39:23,504
You know, he's very...

343
00:39:24,512 --> 00:39:25,638
...intense.

344
00:39:26,647 --> 00:39:27,705
Perhaps.

345
00:39:27,815 --> 00:39:30,682
Actually, I found him to have
quite a sense of humor.

346
00:39:43,864 --> 00:39:45,661
That's a very small room.

347
00:39:46,867 --> 00:39:50,359
Yes, sir, I guess that's true.
Smallest room in the house.

348
00:39:50,438 --> 00:39:52,770
Yes, I... I guess that's true.

349
00:40:12,000 --> 00:40:13,000
Mr. Gardiner

350
00:40:14,195 --> 00:40:17,392
Welcome to Rand Memorial Hospital.

351
00:40:18,866 --> 00:40:21,801
- Thank you.
- Can I help you to the table, Mr. Gardiner?

352
00:40:21,869 --> 00:40:22,995
Thank you.

353
00:40:25,339 --> 00:40:27,170
I feel very good in here.

354
00:40:29,043 --> 00:40:30,442
That's the oxygen.

355
00:40:31,212 --> 00:40:32,975
When I first got sick...

356
00:40:33,481 --> 00:40:37,508
...I had this entire room glassed in...

357
00:40:38,819 --> 00:40:41,652
...so they could pump in
some extra oxygen.

358
00:40:42,590 --> 00:40:44,353
Keeps my spirits up.

359
00:40:46,327 --> 00:40:48,124
You must be very ill.

360
00:40:48,829 --> 00:40:53,000
Aplastic anemia, Mr. Gardiner.
Aplastic anemia.

361
00:40:53,400 --> 00:40:57,131
The bone marrow doesn't supply
enough red blood cells.

362
00:40:58,772 --> 00:41:01,070
Not a damn thing they can do about it.

363
00:41:02,343 --> 00:41:05,005
Ooh, they can keep me comfortable.

364
00:41:05,579 --> 00:41:09,675
Prolong my life with steroid therapy...

365
00:41:10,951 --> 00:41:12,578
...and these transfusions.

366
00:41:14,522 --> 00:41:16,888
But what makes my blood boil...

367
00:41:18,425 --> 00:41:20,859
...that is, what there is of it...

368
00:41:22,096 --> 00:41:24,894
...is that this is usually...

369
00:41:25,533 --> 00:41:27,626
...a young person's disease.

370
00:41:28,636 --> 00:41:31,400
Here I am getting along in years...

371
00:41:32,006 --> 00:41:35,533
...and I'm about to die
of a young person's disease.

372
00:41:40,814 --> 00:41:43,612
I've never seen anything like this
on television.

373
00:41:44,785 --> 00:41:46,810
Please, lie still, Mr. Gardiner.

374
00:41:48,522 --> 00:41:51,389
You'll join us for dinner,
of course Mr. Gardiner.

375
00:41:51,592 --> 00:41:53,753
Oh, yes, please.
Thank you. Thank you.

376
00:41:53,928 --> 00:41:55,293
I'm very hungry.

377
00:41:58,299 --> 00:42:00,062
Yes, and so am l, my boy.

378
00:42:01,702 --> 00:42:03,294
So am I.

379
00:42:09,410 --> 00:42:10,934
Do you know Raphael?

380
00:42:13,781 --> 00:42:15,476
No, sir. I don't believe I do.

381
00:42:16,150 --> 00:42:18,243
Because I have a message for him.

382
00:42:18,485 --> 00:42:19,543
Yes, sir?

383
00:42:19,753 --> 00:42:23,211
A small black man
gave me a message for Raphael.

384
00:42:26,000 --> 00:42:30,593
Well... I still don't believe I know the man,
Mr. Gardiner. Now, please...

385
00:42:31,365 --> 00:42:32,593
...lie still.

386
00:42:49,984 --> 00:42:52,452
Is there anyone we could notify for you?

387
00:42:55,556 --> 00:42:56,545
No.

388
00:42:57,424 --> 00:43:00,621
The old man died and Louise left.

389
00:43:01,498 --> 00:43:05,397
Oh!
I'm... I'm very sorry.

390
00:43:07,400 --> 00:43:08,000
Well...

391
00:43:09,737 --> 00:43:13,434
Well, I do hope your injury won't prevent you
from attending to business, Mr. Gardiner.

392
00:43:16,310 --> 00:43:18,005
Do you need a secretary?

393
00:43:18,812 --> 00:43:20,109
No, thank you.

394
00:43:21,181 --> 00:43:23,081
My house was shut down.

395
00:43:24,553 --> 00:43:29,021
You mean...
You mean your business was shut down?

396
00:43:29,990 --> 00:43:30,922
Yes.

397
00:43:31,792 --> 00:43:34,317
Shut down and closed by the attorneys.

398
00:43:36,163 --> 00:43:39,599
What did I tell you?
That's exactly what I mean.

399
00:43:40,567 --> 00:43:45,061
The businessman today is at the mercy
of kid-lawyers from the SEZ.

400
00:43:46,040 --> 00:43:48,065
It's happening to everyone, I'm afraid.

401
00:43:48,142 --> 00:43:51,510
The way things are going, they'll probably
legislate the medical profession...

402
00:43:51,679 --> 00:43:53,512
...as we know it, right out of existence.

403
00:43:53,714 --> 00:43:56,683
Yes. Right out of existence.

404
00:44:01,121 --> 00:44:03,021
Yeah, it's a damn shame.

405
00:44:05,893 --> 00:44:08,225
What are your plans now, Mr. Gardiner?

406
00:44:08,429 --> 00:44:10,260
Or may I call you Chauncey?

407
00:44:12,399 --> 00:44:13,991
Chauncey's fine.

408
00:44:18,105 --> 00:44:20,471
So then, what are your plans, Chauncey?

409
00:44:25,382 --> 00:44:27,866
Well... I...

410
00:44:28,300 --> 00:44:30,350
I would like to work in your garden.

411
00:44:36,657 --> 00:44:40,093
Ben, I know exactly what he means.
Isn't it wonderful...

412
00:44:40,994 --> 00:44:43,690
...to be with the trees
and the flowers like that?

413
00:44:45,399 --> 00:44:47,458
I never had much feel for it, myself.

414
00:44:49,236 --> 00:44:51,227
I'm a very good gardener.

415
00:44:52,139 --> 00:44:55,734
It's such a... a pleasant way
to forget one's troubles.

416
00:45:00,414 --> 00:45:04,009
Now, isn't that what any businessman is?
A gardener.

417
00:45:05,185 --> 00:45:06,152
He...

418
00:45:07,154 --> 00:45:08,519
...works on...

419
00:45:09,423 --> 00:45:10,822
...flinty soil...

420
00:45:11,759 --> 00:45:13,556
...to make it productive...

421
00:45:13,994 --> 00:45:16,189
...with the labor of his own hands.

422
00:45:16,363 --> 00:45:18,126
He waters it...

423
00:45:18,966 --> 00:45:21,093
...with the sweat of his own brow.

424
00:45:21,902 --> 00:45:25,235
He makes a thing of value for his family...

425
00:45:26,440 --> 00:45:28,169
...and for the community.

426
00:45:28,675 --> 00:45:32,873
Yes, indeed, Chauncey,
a productive businessman...

427
00:45:33,680 --> 00:45:36,581
...is a laborer in the vineyards.

428
00:45:39,720 --> 00:45:41,813
I know exactly what you mean, Ben.

429
00:45:43,424 --> 00:45:46,154
The garden that I left was such a place.

430
00:45:49,730 --> 00:45:53,325
I don't have that anymore. All I have left...

431
00:45:54,201 --> 00:45:55,964
...is the room upstairs.

432
00:45:56,870 --> 00:45:59,430
Oh, come on, now, wait a minute, Chauncey.

433
00:46:00,007 --> 00:46:01,372
You've got your health.

434
00:46:02,276 --> 00:46:06,804
For God's sake, man, you can't let those
bastards get you down. You got to fight.

435
00:46:08,982 --> 00:46:12,543
I don't want to hear anymore from you
about that room upstairs.

436
00:46:13,220 --> 00:46:15,984
That's where I'm going, too damn soon.

437
00:46:27,901 --> 00:46:29,892
It's a very pleasant room, Ben.

438
00:46:31,405 --> 00:46:34,772
I'm sure it is.
That's what they say, anyway.

439
00:46:47,054 --> 00:46:48,214
You know, Chauncey...

440
00:46:50,557 --> 00:46:54,254
...there are thousands of businessmen,
large and small...

441
00:46:55,596 --> 00:46:57,120
...in your situation.

442
00:46:59,766 --> 00:47:00,790
I've...

443
00:47:01,635 --> 00:47:05,127
...given the matter a good deal
of consideration for some time.

444
00:47:06,940 --> 00:47:09,306
They've been harassed long enough by...

445
00:47:10,043 --> 00:47:13,103
...inflation, increased taxation...

446
00:47:13,680 --> 00:47:15,671
...all sorts of indecencies.

447
00:47:15,916 --> 00:47:20,717
After all, they're our strongest defense
against the pollutants...

448
00:47:20,787 --> 00:47:22,516
...of our basic freedoms...

449
00:47:23,524 --> 00:47:26,960
...as well as the well-being
of our middle class.

450
00:47:30,597 --> 00:47:34,431
I've been thinking about starting
a financial assistance fund.

451
00:47:37,271 --> 00:47:41,332
Tell me, would you have any ideas
on that subject?

452
00:47:42,976 --> 00:47:43,840
No, Ben.

453
00:47:46,513 --> 00:47:48,481
Reluctant to speak.

454
00:47:53,000 --> 00:47:56,115
Well... I can understand that.

455
00:47:56,423 --> 00:47:58,323
After a man's lost everything...

456
00:47:58,825 --> 00:48:02,283
...anger tends to block out rationality,
for a while.

457
00:48:04,264 --> 00:48:06,960
But, you work on the idea.

458
00:48:08,669 --> 00:48:09,795
Water it.

459
00:48:10,604 --> 00:48:11,832
Fertilize it.

460
00:48:12,906 --> 00:48:15,033
I will, Ben. Yes.

461
00:48:17,511 --> 00:48:20,446
I'm sure you'll sprout some thoughts
in a few days.

462
00:48:22,215 --> 00:48:24,149
I will, Ben. Yes.

463
00:48:39,633 --> 00:48:40,759
Sorry, sir.

464
00:48:40,968 --> 00:48:45,905
I thought you were going to come out with
another jest about the elevator.

465
00:48:46,373 --> 00:48:47,465
Excuse me.

466
00:48:56,984 --> 00:48:58,008
Elevator.

467
00:49:00,000 --> 00:49:02,085
Yes, sir.
Elevator.

468
00:49:05,885 --> 00:49:06,427
Chauncey!

469
00:49:07,527 --> 00:49:09,859
I just wanted you to know
how delighted I am...

470
00:49:09,930 --> 00:49:13,559
...that you're staying with us
and how dreadful I feel about your leg.

471
00:49:13,667 --> 00:49:14,759
Thank you, Eve.

472
00:49:16,737 --> 00:49:20,503
You lifted Ben's spirits tonight
to such an extent, do you know that?

473
00:49:21,341 --> 00:49:24,071
He liked you so much, Chauncey.
He really did.

474
00:49:26,179 --> 00:49:29,546
Ben is very ill, Eve. I've seen that before.

475
00:49:30,784 --> 00:49:31,808
I know.

476
00:49:32,786 --> 00:49:34,686
He reminds me of the old man.

477
00:49:36,000 --> 00:49:37,212
Oh, does he?

478
00:49:39,000 --> 00:49:44,126
Eve, are you going to leave and close
this house when Ben dies?

479
00:49:48,301 --> 00:49:51,168
Why, I... I... I don't think so.

480
00:49:54,007 --> 00:49:55,099
Goodnight, Eve.

481
00:49:57,944 --> 00:49:59,241
Goodnight, Chauncey.

482
00:50:27,607 --> 00:50:29,541
- 'Morning, Mr. Perkins.
- 'Morning, Mr. Riff.

483
00:50:29,643 --> 00:50:30,667
- Nice to see you.
- Thank You.

484
00:50:30,744 --> 00:50:34,510
We have an additional guest with us today,
Mr. Chauncey Gardiner.

485
00:50:35,248 --> 00:50:38,547
I see. Shall we set up the communications
in the usual place?

486
00:50:38,618 --> 00:50:40,779
- Of course.
- Okay, let's go to work.

487
00:51:09,349 --> 00:51:11,112
Would you like a car, sir?

488
00:51:13,086 --> 00:51:14,815
Yes, I would like a car.

489
00:51:15,021 --> 00:51:16,045
Yes, sir.

490
00:51:16,423 --> 00:51:17,515
Thank you.

491
00:51:19,659 --> 00:51:21,422
Send up Number 7, please.

492
00:51:24,030 --> 00:51:27,431
Chauncey, there you are.
What are you doing on that leg?

493
00:51:28,568 --> 00:51:30,229
It's fine today, Robert.

494
00:51:30,303 --> 00:51:33,238
Oh, shame on you, Chauncey.
You should let me be the judge of that.

495
00:51:33,940 --> 00:51:35,430
Please, sit in the chair.

496
00:51:37,244 --> 00:51:40,611
I swear Chauncey, between you and Benjamin,
I've got my hands full.

497
00:51:42,048 --> 00:51:45,313
Say, that is coming along.
The swelling's gone down considerably.

498
00:51:45,385 --> 00:51:46,818
Your limousine, sir.

499
00:51:50,690 --> 00:51:51,918
Fine. Thank you.

500
00:51:58,431 --> 00:52:00,524
Are you going somewhere?

501
00:52:02,068 --> 00:52:02,898
No.

502
00:52:08,441 --> 00:52:12,502
Anyway, the President's volunteered
to sit in for Ben at the convention.

503
00:52:13,146 --> 00:52:16,377
Quite a nice gesture.
They're due here soon, I believe.

504
00:52:18,285 --> 00:52:20,549
I know about
the President coming, Robert.

505
00:52:21,822 --> 00:52:23,517
- You do, do you?
- Yes.

506
00:52:23,924 --> 00:52:26,358
Ben would like me to meet the President.

507
00:52:26,793 --> 00:52:28,590
- He would, would he?
- Yes.

508
00:52:34,234 --> 00:52:36,361
How will I know
when it's 10:00, Robert?

509
00:52:40,243 --> 00:52:40,890
Well...

510
00:52:43,590 --> 00:52:45,636
...it's 9:10, now.

511
00:52:47,881 --> 00:52:50,213
And if you don't see a clock...

512
00:52:52,586 --> 00:52:54,918
...well, I'm sure
someone will have the time.

513
00:52:56,590 --> 00:52:57,921
I understand.

514
00:52:59,759 --> 00:53:01,249
I'm going to walk.

515
00:53:02,362 --> 00:53:05,195
Walk? Well, yes, hell yes. Walk.

516
00:53:05,832 --> 00:53:08,630
- You're meeting the President, aren't you?
- Yes.

517
00:53:09,936 --> 00:53:11,927
I've watched him on television.

518
00:53:39,366 --> 00:53:41,129
Oh, it's very precise, sir.

519
00:53:42,002 --> 00:53:43,128
It's 10:00.

520
00:53:45,605 --> 00:53:46,970
Thank you, Jim.

521
00:53:51,244 --> 00:53:53,940
Mrs. Aubrey, the President is arriving.

522
00:54:39,270 --> 00:54:39,944
Chauncey!

523
00:54:40,827 --> 00:54:44,558
- Up and around this morning, are you?
- I like to walk, Ben.

524
00:54:44,698 --> 00:54:46,666
Well, that's good news, my boy.

525
00:54:47,934 --> 00:54:50,095
You look much better today, Ben.

526
00:54:52,839 --> 00:54:54,204
It's all make-up.

527
00:54:54,641 --> 00:54:57,075
I asked nurse Teresa to fix me up a bit.

528
00:54:57,644 --> 00:55:01,603
I didn't want the President to think I was
going to die while he was talking to me.

529
00:55:02,582 --> 00:55:03,742
I see.

530
00:55:04,517 --> 00:55:07,247
Yeah, nobody likes
a dying man, Chauncey.

531
00:55:08,455 --> 00:55:10,446
Because nobody knows what death is.

532
00:55:12,459 --> 00:55:15,087
You seem to be an exception, Chauncey.

533
00:55:16,296 --> 00:55:20,494
That's one of the things I admire
about you, your admirable balance.

534
00:55:21,468 --> 00:55:24,301
You seem to be a truly peaceful man.

535
00:55:25,572 --> 00:55:27,938
Thank you, Ben. Thank you.

536
00:55:31,811 --> 00:55:34,109
Nurse Teresa did a very good job there.

537
00:56:55,195 --> 00:56:57,823
Mr. Rand, the President is arriving.

538
00:56:58,865 --> 00:57:03,063
Just show the President into the library.
We'll be along in a few minutes.

539
00:57:05,271 --> 00:57:08,638
An old habit that goes along with power:
Keep them waiting.

540
00:57:10,510 --> 00:57:11,943
Not now, Arthur.

541
00:57:12,078 --> 00:57:13,238
But, sir...

542
00:57:13,646 --> 00:57:16,171
I'm going to meet the President...

543
00:57:17,183 --> 00:57:18,980
...on my own two feet.

544
00:57:21,280 --> 00:57:21,857
Chauncey!

545
00:57:24,157 --> 00:57:25,385
Shall we go?

546
00:57:25,592 --> 00:57:27,423
That's a very good idea, Ben.

547
00:57:44,844 --> 00:57:49,008
When I was younger,
I had thoughts of public office.

548
00:57:49,949 --> 00:57:51,780
But I found, Chauncey,
that...

549
00:57:52,051 --> 00:57:55,919
...I was able to contribute more
as a private citizen.

550
00:57:57,123 --> 00:57:58,351
Of course my...

551
00:57:58,958 --> 00:58:02,621
...wealth provided me
with considerable influence.

552
00:58:03,329 --> 00:58:06,298
But I've tried, Chauncey,
believe me, I've tried...

553
00:58:07,066 --> 00:58:09,364
...not to misuse that power.

554
00:58:10,703 --> 00:58:15,436
It's extremely important Chauncey,
that we don't allow ourselves...

555
00:58:15,508 --> 00:58:19,535
...to become blinded to the needs
of our government...

556
00:58:20,013 --> 00:58:22,675
...no matter how strong the temptation.

557
00:58:23,784 --> 00:58:27,309
Oh, I've been labeled a kingmaker...

558
00:58:27,687 --> 00:58:29,780
...but I've tried...

559
00:58:30,356 --> 00:58:33,553
...to keep myself open
to the voice of the people.

560
00:58:34,561 --> 00:58:37,359
And I've remained honest to myself.

561
00:58:38,231 --> 00:58:39,858
That's the main thing.

562
00:58:39,933 --> 00:58:42,561
- Good morning, Mr. Rand.
- Good morning, gentlemen.

563
00:59:02,522 --> 00:59:04,319
Where the hell is he?

564
00:59:05,725 --> 00:59:07,215
Mr. President.

565
00:59:08,728 --> 00:59:09,786
Ben.

566
00:59:26,312 --> 00:59:28,837
It's good to see you.
You look terrific.

567
00:59:29,449 --> 00:59:31,212
Thank you, Mr. President.

568
00:59:31,784 --> 00:59:34,344
Your visit has helped to raise my spirits.

569
00:59:35,255 --> 00:59:37,519
Well, I've missed you, my friend.

570
00:59:38,558 --> 00:59:41,254
Come, sit down.
Take a load off your feet.

571
00:59:44,530 --> 00:59:46,054
Hello, Mr. President.

572
00:59:49,068 --> 00:59:50,035
Hello.

573
00:59:50,405 --> 00:59:57,001
Mr. President, I want you to meet
my very dear friend, Mr. Chauncey Gardiner.

574
00:59:59,479 --> 01:00:03,745
On television, Mr. President,
you look much smaller.

575
01:00:05,318 --> 01:00:09,186
I must warn you that Chauncey's not a man
to bandy words.

576
01:00:10,423 --> 01:00:12,516
Oh? Really?

577
01:00:15,762 --> 01:00:19,698
Well, Mr. Gardiner, I'm a man who appreciates
discussing a frank discussion.

578
01:00:22,168 --> 01:00:24,659
- Would you be seated?
- Yes, I will.

579
01:00:35,548 --> 01:00:38,346
- Now Ben, I was wondering
if you had a chance...
- Yes?

580
01:00:42,722 --> 01:00:45,350
- Did you happen to have a chance to go...
- Yes?

581
01:00:49,262 --> 01:00:50,820
Ben, did you read my speech?

582
01:00:52,265 --> 01:00:54,324
Overall, pretty good.

583
01:00:55,168 --> 01:00:59,070
But I think, Mr. President,
that it is very dangerous...

584
01:00:59,272 --> 01:01:02,867
...to play around with temporary measures
at a time like this.

585
01:01:03,509 --> 01:01:05,033
Well, Ben, I mean...

586
01:01:05,311 --> 01:01:07,006
I sympathize with you...

587
01:01:07,747 --> 01:01:10,773
...and I know how difficult it is
to be straightforward.

588
01:01:11,984 --> 01:01:13,952
But I'll tell you right now, Bobby...

589
01:01:30,470 --> 01:01:33,098
- Hi.
- Hi. I'm Riff. Secret Service.

590
01:01:33,973 --> 01:01:35,372
Good. Of course.

591
01:01:38,044 --> 01:01:40,444
What you're saying, Ben, is that...

592
01:01:41,581 --> 01:01:45,176
...you don't think I should take the chance.
- Absolutely not.

593
01:01:53,426 --> 01:01:57,419
Mr. Gardiner, do you agree with Ben, or do
you think we can stimulate growth through...

594
01:01:58,698 --> 01:02:00,427
...temporary incentives?

595
01:02:12,078 --> 01:02:14,945
As long as the roots are not severed...

596
01:02:16,015 --> 01:02:17,312
...all is well.

597
01:02:18,050 --> 01:02:19,779
And all will be well...

598
01:02:20,753 --> 01:02:22,118
...in the garden.

599
01:02:27,760 --> 01:02:29,591
- In the garden?
- Yes.

600
01:02:36,836 --> 01:02:40,363
In a garden, growth has its season.

601
01:02:43,209 --> 01:02:45,302
First come spring and summer...

602
01:02:46,446 --> 01:02:48,038
...but then we have...

603
01:02:49,015 --> 01:02:50,880
...fall and winter.

604
01:02:51,984 --> 01:02:55,283
And then we get spring and summer again.

605
01:03:01,060 --> 01:03:02,823
- Spring and summer?
- Yes.

606
01:03:05,598 --> 01:03:07,691
- And fall and winter?
- Yes.

607
01:03:14,574 --> 01:03:19,671
I think what our insightful
young friend is saying...

608
01:03:20,913 --> 01:03:24,371
...is that we welcome the inevitable...

609
01:03:24,717 --> 01:03:26,412
...seasons of nature...

610
01:03:27,920 --> 01:03:31,014
...but we're upset by the seasons
of our economy.

611
01:03:31,491 --> 01:03:32,458
Yes.

612
01:03:33,092 --> 01:03:35,253
There will be growth in the spring.

613
01:03:41,200 --> 01:03:45,102
Oh Mr. Gardiner, I must admit, that is one of
the most refreshing and optimistic statements...

614
01:03:45,204 --> 01:03:47,365
...I've heard in a very very long time.

615
01:03:50,643 --> 01:03:52,634
I admire your good solid sense.

616
01:03:53,312 --> 01:03:55,872
It's precisely what we lack on Capitol Hill.

617
01:04:01,521 --> 01:04:02,954
I must be going.

618
01:04:03,556 --> 01:04:06,525
- This visit has been most enlightening.
- Yes, it has.

619
01:04:08,261 --> 01:04:11,890
And Ben, thank you
for your time and thought.

620
01:04:11,964 --> 01:04:13,431
Oh, nonsense.

621
01:04:13,866 --> 01:04:16,664
Thank you for taking time out
with a dying man.

622
01:04:16,769 --> 01:04:18,703
No, I won't have any of that.

623
01:04:19,005 --> 01:04:21,997
Why don't you listen to your friend,
Chauncey, here?

624
01:04:22,074 --> 01:04:24,406
This is a time to think of life.

625
01:04:27,780 --> 01:04:29,611
That's right, Mr. President.

626
01:04:31,551 --> 01:04:33,314
Now, you take care, Ben.

627
01:04:34,353 --> 01:04:36,321
And you take care, too, Bobby.

628
01:04:40,726 --> 01:04:41,784
Chauncey.

629
01:04:42,695 --> 01:04:43,753
Bobby.

630
01:05:01,213 --> 01:05:03,773
He's a decent fellow, isn't he?
The President.

631
01:05:05,117 --> 01:05:07,608
Yes. I'm glad he came, Ben.

632
01:05:11,524 --> 01:05:15,119
Kaufman, I'll need some information
on Mr. Chauncey Gardiner's background.

633
01:05:15,194 --> 01:05:18,186
- Gardiner, yes, sir.
- And I'd like it sometime today.

634
01:05:18,497 --> 01:05:19,896
No problem, Chief.

635
01:05:35,247 --> 01:05:36,441
You know, Chauncey...

636
01:05:37,984 --> 01:05:41,249
...you don't play games with words...

637
01:05:42,488 --> 01:05:44,115
...to protect yourself.

638
01:05:44,957 --> 01:05:46,925
No, you're direct.

639
01:05:49,962 --> 01:05:53,295
Do you remember what I was talking
to you about last night?

640
01:05:55,701 --> 01:05:58,329
- No, Ben.
- Oh, sure you do.

641
01:05:59,205 --> 01:06:02,606
My plan for a financial assistance
to businessmen.

642
01:06:05,411 --> 01:06:10,508
I think you're just the man to take charge
of an institution like that.

643
01:06:14,286 --> 01:06:15,583
I understand, Ben.

644
01:06:19,550 --> 01:06:25,656
Chauncey, I know you're not a man
to act on the spur of the moment...

645
01:06:26,832 --> 01:06:29,960
...so don't feel that you have to rush
into a decision.

646
01:06:34,940 --> 01:06:36,066
Thank you, Ben.

647
01:06:37,476 --> 01:06:40,775
Now, Chauncey,
I'm afraid I must excuse myself.

648
01:06:42,081 --> 01:06:43,742
I'm awfully tired.

649
01:07:02,268 --> 01:07:04,293
I'm sorry you're so sick, Ben.

650
01:07:32,998 --> 01:07:35,933
We have 60,000
tulip bulbs up there, Chauncey.

651
01:07:36,302 --> 01:07:38,463
It is so glorious when they bloom.

652
01:07:39,538 --> 01:07:41,870
Of course, the roses are my favorites.

653
01:07:42,041 --> 01:07:44,100
We have 20,000 rose bushes.

654
01:07:46,378 --> 01:07:49,472
And over here,
we plant something different every year.

655
01:07:50,149 --> 01:07:53,050
I haven't quite decided
what we'll plant this year.

656
01:07:54,120 --> 01:07:56,145
And that's the gardener's house.

657
01:08:03,395 --> 01:08:05,226
And this is the greenhouse.

658
01:08:08,267 --> 01:08:10,633
I like to watch the young plants grow.

659
01:08:11,570 --> 01:08:13,663
- It's wonderful, isn't it?
- Yes.

660
01:08:14,974 --> 01:08:18,137
Young plants do much better
if a person helps them.

661
01:08:25,651 --> 01:08:26,811
You know, Chauncey...

662
01:08:27,953 --> 01:08:31,855
...Ben told me that the President
was very taken with you this morning.

663
01:08:40,733 --> 01:08:43,861
Chauncey, last night you mentioned
an old man that died.

664
01:08:45,738 --> 01:08:47,933
You must've been very close to him.

665
01:08:48,007 --> 01:08:49,201
I was. Yes.

666
01:08:50,776 --> 01:08:51,936
I'm sorry.

667
01:08:56,148 --> 01:09:00,175
You mentioned also
that Louise had gone, also.

668
01:09:01,520 --> 01:09:03,511
Were you very close to Louise?

669
01:09:03,989 --> 01:09:05,957
Yes, I liked Louise very much.

670
01:09:06,559 --> 01:09:08,026
She was his maid.

671
01:09:09,662 --> 01:09:12,523
- Oh! Oh, his maid.
- Yes.

672
01:09:14,200 --> 01:09:15,792
Oh, I see. I see.

673
01:09:17,403 --> 01:09:20,804
So stupid of me. I thought maybe
she was perhaps someone...

674
01:09:20,873 --> 01:09:24,070
...you were romantically involved with
or maybe a sister.

675
01:09:24,743 --> 01:09:25,675
No.

676
01:09:26,145 --> 01:09:29,342
She used to bring me my meals.

677
01:09:29,682 --> 01:09:31,377
She was very kind to me.

678
01:09:38,791 --> 01:09:43,285
Chauncey Gardiner, Mr. Rand's close friend
and advisor, was at the meeting this morning.

679
01:09:45,564 --> 01:09:49,557
I found Mr. Gardiner to have a feeling
for this country that we need more of.

680
01:09:51,537 --> 01:09:54,734
To quote Mr. Gardiner,
a most intuitive man:

681
01:09:56,308 --> 01:10:00,608
'As long as the roots of industry remain
firmly planted in the national soil...

682
01:10:01,914 --> 01:10:04,747
'...the economic prospects
are undoubtedly sunny. '

683
01:10:09,421 --> 01:10:10,911
- What is it?
- Doctor.

684
01:10:12,091 --> 01:10:13,854
Decoral. Five milligrams.

685
01:10:14,226 --> 01:10:15,989
- Now I know that many of you...
- Put your arms up.

686
01:10:17,329 --> 01:10:18,557
Put your arms up. Ben!

687
01:10:19,698 --> 01:10:21,427
I think you'd better leave, Eve.

688
01:10:21,533 --> 01:10:23,262
- Will he be okay?
- He'll be fine.

689
01:10:23,335 --> 01:10:25,098
Yeah, we got you, Ben.
We  got you.

690
01:10:27,172 --> 01:10:28,833
Come on, Chauncey.

691
01:10:29,675 --> 01:10:32,701
But I have decided
there are no temporary stopgaps.

692
01:10:34,346 --> 01:10:37,645
So I'm going to rethink my position
and find another solution.

693
01:10:38,918 --> 01:10:40,886
You'll be very pleased to know that your...

694
01:10:40,986 --> 01:10:43,113
...founder and Chairman of the Board...

695
01:10:43,222 --> 01:10:46,385
...Mr. Benjamin Turnbull Rand,
agrees with me on this...

696
01:10:47,126 --> 01:10:48,286
...for once.

697
01:10:52,498 --> 01:10:56,901
Gentlemen, let us not fear the inevitable
chill and storms of autumn and winter.

698
01:10:57,069 --> 01:11:00,334
Instead, let us anticipate
the rapid growth of springtime.

699
01:11:01,240 --> 01:11:03,401
Let us await the rewards of summer.

700
01:11:04,410 --> 01:11:07,470
As in a garden of the earth,
let us learn to accept...

701
01:11:07,579 --> 01:11:10,207
...and appreciate the times
when the trees are bare...

702
01:11:10,849 --> 01:11:13,545
...as well as the times
when we pick the fruit.

703
01:11:17,557 --> 01:11:22,591
Chauncey, I'm just so very grateful
that you're here with us.

704
01:11:23,996 --> 01:11:25,463
So am l, Eve.

705
01:11:27,766 --> 01:11:29,631
It's been an exhausting day for Ben.

706
01:11:30,369 --> 01:11:33,167
He's resting now,
and there's no cause for alarm.

707
01:11:33,306 --> 01:11:36,565
Oh, Mr. Gardiner,
I have a telephone call for you.

708
01:11:39,378 --> 01:11:40,709
Telephone call?

709
01:11:41,313 --> 01:11:45,443
Yes. Sidney Courtney, the financial editor
of the Washington Post.

710
01:11:49,221 --> 01:11:51,246
Would you care to take it, sir?

711
01:11:53,425 --> 01:11:54,323
Yes.

712
01:11:55,160 --> 01:11:56,627
In my office.

713
01:12:08,440 --> 01:12:10,806
Go! Go Chauncey, I'll be just fine.

714
01:12:13,712 --> 01:12:15,202
Yes, you'll be fine, Eve.

715
01:12:27,326 --> 01:12:29,487
He's such a kind and sensitive man.

716
01:12:30,562 --> 01:12:31,824
Don't you think?

717
01:12:48,180 --> 01:12:50,205
- He's not there.
- Not there?

718
01:12:52,518 --> 01:12:54,349
Mr. Courtney, are you there?

719
01:12:55,687 --> 01:12:57,120
Oh yes, he's there.

720
01:13:03,228 --> 01:13:05,059
Where is he? There or here?

721
01:13:06,198 --> 01:13:07,688
He's on both lines.

722
01:13:19,411 --> 01:13:20,901
Are you there?

723
01:13:21,880 --> 01:13:23,347
Yes, I'm here.

724
01:13:23,916 --> 01:13:25,440
Hello, Mr. Gardiner.

725
01:13:26,118 --> 01:13:29,645
I saw the President's speech
at the Financial Institute today.

726
01:13:29,721 --> 01:13:31,279
Would you care to comment...

727
01:13:31,924 --> 01:13:35,382
...on the meeting between Mr. Rand
and the President and yourself?

728
01:13:36,462 --> 01:13:39,761
Yes. It was very nice meeting...

729
01:13:40,199 --> 01:13:41,257
...the President.

730
01:13:41,867 --> 01:13:44,631
What we'd like to know are some facts.

731
01:13:44,870 --> 01:13:48,465
Such as, what is the exact relationship
between yourself and the...

732
01:13:48,907 --> 01:13:51,205
...First American Financial Corporation?

733
01:13:51,477 --> 01:13:53,775
I think you should ask Mr. Rand that.

734
01:13:54,646 --> 01:13:59,208
Well, yes, sir. But Mr. Rand is ill,
so I'm taking the liberty of asking you.

735
01:14:02,688 --> 01:14:04,553
What? Say that again.

736
01:14:06,391 --> 01:14:11,124
I said that since Mr. Rand is ill,
I'm taking the liberty of asking you.

737
01:14:11,964 --> 01:14:13,329
Yes, you are.

738
01:14:14,166 --> 01:14:16,066
You should ask Mr. Rand that.

739
01:14:17,536 --> 01:14:18,867
Of course.

740
01:14:21,206 --> 01:14:23,697
Just one quick question, Mr. Gardiner...

741
01:14:34,553 --> 01:14:36,214
Will you hold a minute, please?

742
01:14:38,091 --> 01:14:42,754
Mr. Gardiner, I have the producer
of The Gary Burns Show on the line.

743
01:14:43,162 --> 01:14:46,188
Oh yes, I have watched that show.

744
01:14:46,732 --> 01:14:50,429
Of course. They would like you to appear
on the show tonight.

745
