01:32:51,115 --> 01:32:54,278
'F-R-l-E-N-D

993
01:32:54,552 --> 01:32:57,453
'Special. You are my friend

994
01:32:58,756 --> 01:33:01,088
'You're special to me'

995
01:33:36,888 --> 01:33:39,394
Oh... oh...

996
01:33:40,394 --> 01:33:41,899
Oh, Chauncey!

997
01:33:42,099 --> 01:33:43,566
Thank you.

998
01:33:44,201 --> 01:33:45,725
Oh, I'm so grateful, Chauncey.

999
01:33:48,973 --> 01:33:50,463
I would've just...

1000
01:33:51,609 --> 01:33:54,544
...opened up
at the slightest touch.

1001
01:33:55,546 --> 01:33:58,606
I would've just opened up. You know?
You know that.

1002
01:34:00,751 --> 01:34:02,548
But you're so strong...

1003
01:34:03,721 --> 01:34:05,985
...that I can trust myself with you.

1004
01:34:08,025 --> 01:34:10,016
I'm glad you didn't open, Eve.

1005
01:34:38,589 --> 01:34:41,786
Well, a long time ago,
people didn't have television...

1006
01:34:42,727 --> 01:34:45,890
...but they still liked to look
at interesting pictures.

1007
01:34:46,530 --> 01:34:49,055
And they would put pictures like these...

1008
01:34:49,533 --> 01:34:51,558
- Thank you.
...in a special viewer.

1009
01:34:52,169 --> 01:34:56,833
They would look at them very carefully.
I'll show you another one.

1010
01:35:04,181 --> 01:35:05,910
They looked like cards.

1011
01:35:06,217 --> 01:35:08,685
Flash cards for schools or something.

1012
01:35:09,253 --> 01:35:13,349
But they're really photographs.
Take a careful look at them.

1013
01:35:14,091 --> 01:35:17,151
The interesting thing about them,
is that they're two.

1014
01:35:17,595 --> 01:35:18,653
- What?
- Two.

1015
01:35:19,130 --> 01:35:21,064
And they look very much alike.

1016
01:35:21,866 --> 01:35:23,561
Here, I'll show you another one.

1017
01:35:26,604 --> 01:35:28,435
Mr. Thomas Franklin, please.

1018
01:35:34,311 --> 01:35:35,801
Is Mr. Franklin in?

1019
01:35:36,914 --> 01:35:39,382
Certainly. This is Dr. Robert Allenby.

1020
01:35:40,384 --> 01:35:43,615
Would you tell Mr. Franklin
that I'd like to speak to him?

1021
01:35:44,054 --> 01:35:46,614
It concerns Chauncey Gardiner.

1022
01:36:07,311 --> 01:36:11,714
Mr. Gardiner, what was your reaction to the
Post's editorial on the President's speech?

1023
01:36:13,083 --> 01:36:14,607
I did not read that.

1024
01:36:15,319 --> 01:36:19,619
- But, sir, you must've at least glanced at it.
- I did not glance at it.

1025
01:36:19,723 --> 01:36:23,215
Mr. Gardiner, the New York Times spoke
of your 'peculiar brand of optimism.'

1026
01:36:23,294 --> 01:36:27,162
- What was your reaction to that?
- I do not know what it means.

1027
01:36:28,365 --> 01:36:31,630
Sorry to persist, sir,
but it would be of great interest to me...

1028
01:36:31,735 --> 01:36:34,101
...to know just what newspapers
you do read.

1029
01:36:35,473 --> 01:36:38,033
I do not read papers. I watch TV.

1030
01:36:38,742 --> 01:36:39,626
Do you mean Mr. Gardiner,

1031
01:36:39,726 --> 01:36:44,510
that you find television's coverage of the
news superior to that of the newspapers'?

1032
01:36:45,182 --> 01:36:46,877
I like to watch TV.

1033
01:36:47,451 --> 01:36:48,543
Thank you, Mr. Gardiner.

1034
01:36:49,487 --> 01:36:50,818
You're welcome.

1035
01:36:51,656 --> 01:36:56,256
Well, few men in public life have the courage
not to read the newspapers.

1036
01:36:56,727 --> 01:37:00,754
None, that this reporter has met,
had the guts to admit it.

1037
01:37:04,635 --> 01:37:08,104
Chauncey, I've never seen anyone
handle the press the way you do.

1038
01:37:08,239 --> 01:37:10,070
You're so cool and detached.

1039
01:37:10,908 --> 01:37:12,000
Thank you, Eve.

1040
01:37:12,500 --> 01:37:13,912
- Eve!
- Sophia!

1041
01:37:15,012 --> 01:37:17,412
- How are you?
- I'm fine. How are you?

1042
01:37:17,481 --> 01:37:20,541
I'm very well.
I'd like you to meet Chauncey Gardiner.

1043
01:37:21,151 --> 01:37:22,584
Hello, Vladimir.

1044
01:37:22,786 --> 01:37:25,016
And this is Mrs. Skrapinov.

1045
01:37:25,890 --> 01:37:28,324
- Natasha.
- Hello, Natasha.

1046
01:37:28,459 --> 01:37:30,950
- Very nice meeting you.
- And you.

1047
01:37:31,395 --> 01:37:35,297
You must sit with us, my friends.
We have much to discuss.

1048
01:37:35,366 --> 01:37:36,000
I agree.

1049
01:37:36,133 --> 01:37:40,267
Eve, let's let the men talk.
Would you two excuse us for a moment?

1050
01:37:40,738 --> 01:37:44,731
Regretfully, we shall yield
the pleasure of your company to others.

1051
01:37:45,509 --> 01:37:47,272
I shall yield, too, Eve.

1052
01:37:48,245 --> 01:37:50,770
Yes.
Well, you have a nice chat.

1053
01:37:54,418 --> 01:37:59,219
Shouldn't we, Mr. Gardiner, get together
more often to exchange our thoughts?

1054
01:37:59,924 --> 01:38:02,518
It's strictly at the rumor stage now, Lyman.

1055
01:38:03,193 --> 01:38:07,391
- But there's something in the wind.
- Something rather big in the wind, I'd say.

1056
01:38:07,464 --> 01:38:11,525
So whose files were destroyed?
The CIA's or the FBI's?

1057
01:38:12,236 --> 01:38:13,464
I don't know.

1058
01:38:14,171 --> 01:38:18,130
You may find, my friend,
that we are not so far from each other.

1059
01:38:18,409 --> 01:38:19,637
Not so far.

1060
01:38:21,745 --> 01:38:23,872
We are not so far from each other.

1061
01:38:24,448 --> 01:38:26,439
Our chairs are almost touching.

1062
01:38:29,320 --> 01:38:30,344
Bravo.

1063
01:38:31,455 --> 01:38:34,288
Our chairs are indeed almost touching.

1064
01:38:34,758 --> 01:38:37,591
And we want to remain seated on them,
correct?

1065
01:38:38,162 --> 01:38:41,097
We don't want them snatched out
from under us, am I right?

1066
01:38:41,165 --> 01:38:44,601
Because, if one goes, the other goes.

1067
01:38:45,135 --> 01:38:47,865
And then boom-boom and boom-boom.

1068
01:38:49,607 --> 01:38:53,566
What is it about his background
that they're trying to cover up?

1069
01:38:54,144 --> 01:38:58,444
A criminal record? A membership
in a subversive organization?

1070
01:38:58,582 --> 01:39:00,106
Homosexual, perhaps.

1071
01:39:00,217 --> 01:39:03,380
He told me that he had been living there
since he was a child...

1072
01:39:03,487 --> 01:39:05,250
...working as a gardener.

1073
01:39:05,589 --> 01:39:09,047
He showed us a room in the garage,
where he said he stayed, and...

1074
01:39:09,159 --> 01:39:13,152
...well, I didn't really believe him,
of course, but why the act?

1075
01:39:17,434 --> 01:39:19,626
Tell me, Mr. Gardiner...

1076
01:39:20,070 --> 01:39:23,506
...do you, by any chance,
enjoy Krylov's fables?

1077
01:39:24,575 --> 01:39:27,510
Now, I ask you that
because there is something...

1078
01:39:28,579 --> 01:39:31,173
...there is something
Krylovian about you.

1079
01:39:34,585 --> 01:39:35,847
Do you think so?

1080
01:39:37,421 --> 01:39:39,855
I believe that you know Krylov.

1081
01:39:51,935 --> 01:39:55,200
So, you know your Krylov in Russian,
do you?

1082
01:39:55,606 --> 01:39:58,837
Mr. Gardiner, I must confess,
I had suspected as much all along.

1083
01:40:01,679 --> 01:40:04,512
Excuse me, but would you tell me
your name again?

1084
01:40:06,150 --> 01:40:08,675
A dash of American humor.

1085
01:40:09,953 --> 01:40:11,420
Vladimir Skrapinov.

1086
01:40:12,756 --> 01:40:14,451
That's a very nice name.

1087
01:40:15,259 --> 01:40:18,592
And yours, Chauncey Gardiner.

1088
01:40:32,376 --> 01:40:37,211
He must have been involved
on some major financial level...

1089
01:40:37,281 --> 01:40:38,578
...with the deceased.

1090
01:40:38,649 --> 01:40:40,412
- With who?
- Mr. Jennings.

1091
01:40:41,652 --> 01:40:46,055
But our firm has no record
of any such transactions.

1092
01:40:48,692 --> 01:40:52,719
Chauncey, you had the Russian ambassador
eating right out of your hand. You know that?

1093
01:40:53,263 --> 01:40:56,061
I didn't know you spoke Russian.
It's incredible.

1094
01:40:56,567 --> 01:40:59,161
It is extremely useful
to speak Russian today.

1095
01:40:59,436 --> 01:41:03,133
- Are you proficient in other languages?
- He's so modest, Ambassador Gaufridi.

1096
01:41:03,540 --> 01:41:06,100
He just never advertises
his accomplishments.

1097
01:41:12,883 --> 01:41:15,147
Maybe you should talk to somebody,
darling.

1098
01:41:15,219 --> 01:41:16,049
No.

1099
01:41:20,591 --> 01:41:22,525
No, that wouldn't do any good.

1100
01:41:27,131 --> 01:41:29,725
Hello, Ronald. How are you?

1101
01:41:29,933 --> 01:41:33,096
- Just fine.
- Good. I am fine, too.

1102
01:41:33,337 --> 01:41:36,306
- Good. Good...
- Yes. Good. We're fine.

1103
01:41:36,373 --> 01:41:37,499
Yeah, fine.

1104
01:41:38,942 --> 01:41:42,673
My editors and I have been wondering
if you'd consider writing a book for us.

1105
01:41:42,746 --> 01:41:46,238
Something about your political philosophy.
What do you say?

1106
01:41:47,017 --> 01:41:49,952
- I can't write.
- Of course not. Who can, nowadays?

1107
01:41:50,020 --> 01:41:53,353
I have trouble writing a postcard
to my children.

1108
01:41:53,457 --> 01:41:56,017
Look, we can give you a six-figure advance.

1109
01:41:56,126 --> 01:41:59,823
I'll provide you with the very best
ghost writer, proofreaders...

1110
01:42:00,230 --> 01:42:02,664
- I can't read.
- Of course, you can't.

1111
01:42:03,167 --> 01:42:04,930
No one has the time.

1112
01:42:05,035 --> 01:42:07,629
We glance at things, we watch television.

1113
01:42:10,340 --> 01:42:12,240
I like to watch TV.

1114
01:42:13,010 --> 01:42:15,171
I'm sure you do. No one reads.

1115
01:42:16,446 --> 01:42:19,040
He's very, very sexy.

1116
01:42:19,516 --> 01:42:22,144
Don't leave me alone with him for too long.

1117
01:42:24,054 --> 01:42:26,488
You say, he showed you his garden.

1118
01:42:26,590 --> 01:42:29,457
Well, he said it was his.
He walked us through it.

1119
01:42:30,694 --> 01:42:31,683
I see.

1120
01:42:33,330 --> 01:42:36,561
Mr. Franklin, I must ask you
and Ms. Hayes...

1121
01:42:36,633 --> 01:42:40,296
...to keep this incident with Mr. Gardiner
strictly to yourselves.

1122
01:42:40,871 --> 01:42:43,669
There's no telling
what he could have been involved in.

1123
01:42:43,740 --> 01:42:46,641
It may be an extremely confidential matter.

1124
01:42:47,411 --> 01:42:50,574
- Please, not a word.
- Of course, Doctor. I understand.

1125
01:42:50,681 --> 01:42:51,579
Fine.

1126
01:42:52,115 --> 01:42:55,209
- Thank you very much.
- Certainly. Glad to be of help.

1127
01:43:03,493 --> 01:43:05,358
Well, I heard he speaks eight languages.

1128
01:43:05,429 --> 01:43:09,092
And on top of everything else,
holds a degree in medicine as well as law.

1129
01:43:09,166 --> 01:43:10,531
Isn't that true, Eve?

1130
01:43:11,068 --> 01:43:14,196
I don't know, Senator,
but it wouldn't surprise me.

1131
01:43:14,805 --> 01:43:16,432
He's very attractive.

1132
01:43:17,174 --> 01:43:18,198
Isn't he?

1133
01:43:18,942 --> 01:43:22,343
You know, I've never met anyone like you
in Washington before.

1134
01:43:23,013 --> 01:43:25,038
Yes, I've been here all my life.

1135
01:43:25,148 --> 01:43:26,137
Really?

1136
01:43:26,216 --> 01:43:29,549
And where have you been all my life?

1137
01:43:33,090 --> 01:43:34,853
Tell me, Mr. Gardiner...

1138
01:43:37,194 --> 01:43:39,526
...have you ever had sex with a man?

1139
01:43:44,735 --> 01:43:47,363
No. I don't think so.

1140
01:43:49,706 --> 01:43:51,697
We could go upstairs right now.

1141
01:43:53,777 --> 01:43:55,677
Is there a TV upstairs?

1142
01:43:58,382 --> 01:43:59,781
I like to watch.

1143
01:44:00,517 --> 01:44:02,644
You like to watch?

1144
01:44:03,020 --> 01:44:03,952
Yes.

1145
01:44:05,022 --> 01:44:07,547
You wait right here. I'll go get Warren.

1146
01:44:16,333 --> 01:44:17,595
Is it me?

1147
01:44:18,835 --> 01:44:22,202
- Is it something I've done?
- No, sweetheart, it's not...

1148
01:44:24,474 --> 01:44:25,634
No, it's...

1149
01:44:26,510 --> 01:44:27,738
It's not you.

1150
01:44:31,114 --> 01:44:33,639
This never happened
when you were a senator.

1151
01:44:34,184 --> 01:44:36,550
It's not that, it's just that I...

1152
01:44:39,990 --> 01:44:42,925
- Yeah, Kaufman, what is it?
- The CIA or the FBI...

1153
01:44:43,193 --> 01:44:45,855
...destroyed Gardiner's files.
- What? Why?

1154
01:44:47,898 --> 01:44:50,731
- Neither agency will admit to a thing.
- All right.

1155
01:44:51,802 --> 01:44:54,930
Get Baldwin and Honeycutt over here.
I'll be right down.

1156
01:45:17,294 --> 01:45:18,955
I feel so close to you, Chauncey.

1157
01:45:20,731 --> 01:45:22,198
I feel safe.

1158
01:45:25,068 --> 01:45:28,868
Ben understands my feelings for you,
by the way, and he accepts them.

1159
01:45:32,209 --> 01:45:33,836
Ben is very wise.

1160
01:45:45,555 --> 01:45:48,854
Or thirdly, the man's files
have been destroyed.

1161
01:45:51,228 --> 01:45:54,595
- Now, I'd like some answers.
- Gardiner's not a foreign agent.

1162
01:45:54,664 --> 01:45:57,098
There are now 16 countries
investigating the man.

1163
01:46:01,605 --> 01:46:02,572
I see.

1164
01:46:03,573 --> 01:46:05,473
What about the third question?

1165
01:46:05,542 --> 01:46:08,102
Is it possible to erase all traces of a man?

1166
01:46:08,311 --> 01:46:09,835
Highly unlikely, sir.

1167
01:46:10,013 --> 01:46:12,948
In fact, the boys around the Bureau feel...

1168
01:46:14,084 --> 01:46:17,315
...that the only one
capable of pulling this off...

1169
01:46:18,221 --> 01:46:20,018
...would be an ex-FBI man.

1170
01:46:23,427 --> 01:46:25,952
I don't think that's entirely true, Grover.

1171
01:46:28,098 --> 01:46:30,931
What do the boys around Intelligence feel?

1172
01:46:33,937 --> 01:46:37,236
Well, Mr. President,
they don't quite know...

1173
01:46:43,080 --> 01:46:44,707
It's very difficult...

1174
01:46:47,117 --> 01:46:49,278
...for me to say goodnight to you, Chauncey.

1175
01:46:50,754 --> 01:46:52,381
It's very hard...

1176
01:46:54,458 --> 01:46:56,153
...for me to leave you.

1177
01:46:57,494 --> 01:46:59,428
It's very hard for me, too, Eve.

1178
01:47:19,416 --> 01:47:20,246
No.

1179
01:47:21,551 --> 01:47:24,019
Sell all 750,000 shares...

1180
01:47:25,755 --> 01:47:27,086
...of CCT.

1181
01:47:30,393 --> 01:47:31,519
Let's see.

1182
01:47:37,968 --> 01:47:40,493
Sell a million shares of Inland Oil.

1183
01:47:42,806 --> 01:47:44,068
Or Mrs. Aubrey...

1184
01:47:46,543 --> 01:47:49,603
...have 30,000 shares of Standard...

1185
01:47:51,014 --> 01:47:53,414
...transferred into your account.

1186
01:47:55,452 --> 01:47:56,749
That's for you.

1187
01:47:58,100 --> 01:47:58,727
Ben

1188
01:48:01,500 --> 01:48:02,200
Robert

1189
01:48:04,327 --> 01:48:07,660
I was just cleaning up some loose ends.

1190
01:48:09,399 --> 01:48:11,833
Getting rid of the dead wood, so...

1191
01:48:13,036 --> 01:48:15,129
...so Eve wouldn't have to cope with it.

1192
01:48:21,500 --> 01:48:25,079
Ben, I'd like to talk to you about Chauncey.

1193
01:48:28,579 --> 01:48:29,091
Chauncey...

1194
01:48:34,191 --> 01:48:35,453
You know, Robert...

1195
01:48:37,394 --> 01:48:39,589
...there's something about him, that...

1196
01:48:40,430 --> 01:48:41,863
...that I trust.

1197
01:48:43,767 --> 01:48:45,462
He makes me feel good.

1198
01:48:49,506 --> 01:48:51,269
Since he's been around...

1199
01:48:53,910 --> 01:48:56,105
...the thought of dying...

1200
01:48:57,681 --> 01:48:59,672
...has been much easier for me.

1201
01:49:46,998 --> 01:49:49,922
Chauncey!
I couldn't stand it.

1202
01:50:46,589 --> 01:50:47,783
What is it?

1203
01:50:49,326 --> 01:50:50,588
Chauncey, what's wrong?

1204
01:50:58,802 --> 01:51:00,235
What's the matter, Chauncey?

1205
01:51:04,741 --> 01:51:07,369
I don't know what you like. I'm sorry.

1206
01:51:07,510 --> 01:51:08,943
I like to watch, Eve.

1207
01:51:11,047 --> 01:51:13,242
What do you mean, you like to watch?

1208
01:51:14,517 --> 01:51:16,109
I like to watch.

1209
01:51:30,633 --> 01:51:31,759
You mean...

1210
01:51:32,836 --> 01:51:34,827
...me, you like to watch me...

1211
01:51:36,206 --> 01:51:37,264
...do it.

1212
01:51:38,308 --> 01:51:39,605
It's very good, Eve.

1213
01:51:50,754 --> 01:51:53,587
No, thanks. I never touch the stuff, never.

1214
01:51:54,791 --> 01:51:56,315
A cigar, then?

1215
01:51:56,459 --> 01:51:58,518
I'll have one of those. Thanks.

1216
01:52:00,063 --> 01:52:01,553
Thanks very much.

1217
01:52:03,867 --> 01:52:05,858
- Sit down, Rico.
- Yeah, thanks.

1218
01:52:14,344 --> 01:52:15,868
Now listen, Rico...

1219
01:52:17,247 --> 01:52:21,047
...I'm going to talk to you, but
you're not going to hear a word I say, see?

1220
01:52:23,319 --> 01:52:27,415
This is inside dope and if it gets out,
it'll be just too bad for somebody.

1221
01:52:27,557 --> 01:52:28,717
You know me.

1222
01:52:29,993 --> 01:52:33,451
All right. Get this.
Pete Montana 's through.

1223
01:52:39,636 --> 01:52:42,537
- And I thought he was such a big guy.
- He's through.

1224
01:52:44,808 --> 01:52:49,074
Suppose I were to tell you that,
from now on, you are Pete Montana.

1225
01:52:50,079 --> 01:52:53,571
That you were to take over his territory
in addition to your own.

1226
01:52:54,684 --> 01:52:56,015
Will you shake on it?

1227
01:52:56,152 --> 01:52:59,610
One of the first things you should know
about me, my darling...

1228
01:53:00,523 --> 01:53:02,650
...is that I'm a little shy.

1229
01:53:03,326 --> 01:53:04,850
All right, it's set.

1230
01:53:06,596 --> 01:53:09,793
I'm doing a lot for you, Rico.
When I get you planted...

1231
01:53:10,233 --> 01:53:13,430
- ...I'll expect plenty of service.
- You'll sure get it.

1232
01:53:14,070 --> 01:53:17,335
Permit me then to drink to the new boss
of the North Side.

